- - - ( JavaScript HTML & DOM Modification Guide ) - - - 



** ( HTML & JS that will be used in examples ): 

• HTML: 
<div id="myDiv"> Hello </div>

• JS: 
let UserElement = document.getElementById("myDiv");



** ( Creating Elements ):

- Creates a new HTML element node of the given tag name.

- This does not place the element into the DOM yet—it only exists in memory.


( Syntax & Example ): 

• document.createElement(tagName)

• const UserElement = document.createElement("div");



** ( SET / ADD, Attributes & Content ):

======================================================

1) ( UserElement.id = "value" ):

- Directly gets or sets the id attribute of the element

- Equivalent to setAttribute("id", value), but cleaner for just the id


( Example ):

• JS:
UserElement.id = "mainBox";

• HTML:
<div id="mainBox"> Hello </div>

======================================================

2) ( UserElement.setAttribute(name, value) ):

- Sets an HTML attribute on the element ( e.g... id, class, src, href, etc... )

- You can use this to dynamically style or identify elements.


( Example ):

• JS:
UserElement.setAttribute("id", "box1");
UserElement.setAttribute("class", "box2");

• HTML:
<div id="box1" class="box2"> Hello </div>
    
======================================================

3) ( UserElement.textContent = "Your Text" ):

-  Sets or Gets the plain text inside an element (HTML tags will be escaped).


( Example ):

• JS: 
UserElement.textContent = "Sample Text"

• HTML:
<div id="myDiv"> Sample Text </div>

======================================================

4) ( UserElement.innerHTML = "Your Content" ):

- Gets or sets the HTML content inside the element (excluding the element tag itself)

- Replaces or returns only the inner part — child elements, tags, or text


( Example ):

• JS:
UserElement.innerHTML = "<strong>Bold</strong>";

• HTML:
<div id="myDiv"> <strong>Bold</strong> content </div>

======================================================

5) ( UserElement.outerHTML = "Your Content" ):

- Gets or sets the HTML content inside the element (excluding the element tag itself)

- Replaces or returns only the inner part — child elements, tags, or text


( Example ):

• JS:
UserElement.innerHTML = "<p>New element</p>";

• HTML:
<p>New element</p>



** ( Append an ELEMENT to DOM ):

- document.body.append(UserElement) 
• Adds the element to the end of <body> (as the last child)

- document.body.prepend(UserElement) 
• Adds the element to the beginning of <body> (as the first child)

- document.body.getElementByID("Existing ID").append(UserElement) 
• Adds the element to the end of the specified element (as its last child)

- document.body.getElementByID("Existing ID").append(UserElement) 
• Adds the element to the beginning of the specified element (as its first child)



** ( Inserting Raw HTML Strings ):

- Inserts a string of HTML at the specified position relative to the element.

- Does not destroy or overwrite existing children.


( Syntax ):
insertAdjacentHTML(position, string)


( Positions ):
• "beforebegin"
• "afterbegin"
• "beforeend"
• "afterend"


( Example ):
UserElement.insertAdjacentHTML("beforeend", "<p>Appended HTML</p>");



** ( Replace & Remove an HTML Element ):


( Remove ):

- UserElement.remove() or document.ElementSelector("node list").remove();
• Completely removes the element itself from the DOM
• Does not need to access the parent — direct and simple

- parentElement.removeChild(UserElement) 
• Removes a child element from its parent
• You must have a reference to the parent element

- document.ElementSelector(".container").removeChild(UserElement);
• Selects the element with class "container" from the DOM
• Removes the specified child element from it (must be a direct child)


( Replace ):

- parentElement.replaceChild(newChild, oldChild)
• Replaces an existing child element with a new one
• You need access to both the parent and the element being replaced

- oldElement.replaceWith(newElement)
• Directly replaces an element with another
• You only need a reference to the element being replaced (no parent needed)